// Persian / Zoroastrian Yazatas × 12 — Ahura Mazda + the six Amesha Spentas +
// the five most-popular Yazatas of the Avestan corpus. SEO funnel at
// /gab44/persian-yazatas (index) + /gab44/persian-yazatas/{slug}.
//
// FOURTEENTH pantheon on gab44. Closes the largest remaining Old-World
// civilizational gap (Persian-Iranian-Zoroastrian sits structurally between
// Mesopotamian and Hindu and is foundational to Abrahamic dualism — the
// Judeo-Christian-Islamic Satan / angels / messiah / end-times / soul-judgment
// / heaven-and-hell / bodily-resurrection complex is canonically downstream
// of the Zoroastrian Ahriman / Yazatas / Saoshyant / Chinvat-Bridge /
// Frashokereti / Garodman-and-Druj-demana eschatology, per the scholarly
// consensus from Mary Boyce through Prods Oktor Skjærvø).
//
// Source corpus per page: the Gathas (the 17 hymns of Zarathustra himself,
// c. 1200-1000 BCE, the oldest surviving Indo-Iranian poetic text and the
// only direct words of the prophet), the Yasna (the 72-chapter priestly
// liturgy that frames the Gathas), the 21 Yashts (hymns to individual
// Yazatas, including the long Mihr-Yasht to Mithra and the long
// Aban-Yasht to Anahita), the Vendidad (the priestly code of purity and
// daeva-rejection), the Bundahishn (the Pahlavi-Middle-Persian creation-
// account), the Denkard (the 9th-c. Pahlavi encyclopedia), the Selections
// of Zadspram, plus modern scholarship: Mary Boyce's three-volume *A
// History of Zoroastrianism* (1975-1991) and *Zoroastrians: Their
// Religious Beliefs and Practices* (1979), Albert de Jong, Almut Hintze
// (*A Zoroastrian Liturgy: The Worship in Seven Chapters*), Prods Oktor
// Skjærvø's Harvard Avesta corpus, Jenny Rose's *Zoroastrianism: An
// Introduction* (2011), Touraj Daryaee's *Sasanian Persia* (2009).
//
// Three families × 4 yazatas:
//
//   1. Ahura Mazda & the Cosmic Triad (Ahura Mazda, Vohu Manah, Asha
//      Vahishta, Khshathra Vairya) — the Wise Lord and the three abstract
//      Amesha Spentas of Good-Mind / Best-Truth / Desirable-Dominion that
//      together compose the masculine-cognitive-cosmic axis of the
//      Zoroastrian heptad.
//
//   2. Earth, Waters, Plants, Royal-Waters (Spenta Armaiti, Haurvatat,
//      Ameretat, Anahita) — the three feminine Amesha Spentas of
//      Holy-Devotion / Wholeness-Health / Immortality plus the popular
//      Yazata Aredvi Sura Anahita whose water-of-the-female-cosmic-river
//      cult was the most-state-supported female cult of Achaemenid and
//      Sasanian Persia.
//
//   3. Covenant, Obedience, Victory, Fire (Mithra, Sraosha, Verethragna,
//      Atar) — the four popular Yazatas who structure the Zoroastrian
//      ritual day: Mithra the covenant-sun-friendship, Sraosha the
//      obedience-prayer-soul-weigher, Verethragna the ten-formed warrior
//      of victory-over-resistance, Atar the eternal fire of every
//      Fire-Temple from the Adur-Burzen-Mihr of Sasanian Parthia to the
//      Atash Behram of contemporary Yazd and Udvada.
//
// Shadow-honest: each page names (a) the 651 CE Arab Muslim conquest of
// Sasanian Persia under Yazdegerd III, the imposition of jizya, the
// systematic conversion of the population over four centuries, the
// destruction of most Fire Temples, and the 10th-c. Parsi migration to
// Gujarat that preserved the tradition in diaspora; (b) the contemporary
// ~25,000 Iranian Zoroastrians as a recognized-but-restricted minority
// under the 1979 Islamic Republic (one reserved Majles seat, mandatory
// hijab for women in public, restrictions on Fire Temple expansion);
// (c) the Western appropriation of Zoroastrian elements stripped of
// context — the Roman Mithras-cult (1st-4th c. CE Mithraea across the
// empire, a male-only secret-mystery cult completely disconnected from
// Iranian Mithra, mistakenly equated as "the same religion" by amateur
// historians); Nietzsche's *Also sprach Zarathustra* (1883) using the
// prophet's name as cipher for the Nietzschean superman with virtually
// no connection to historical Zarathustra's teaching; the Faravahar
// winged-disc symbol stripped from Zoroastrian-ethical-context and
// deployed as Persian-nationalist tattoo / Iranian-Pahlavi-monarchist
// emblem / Iranian-diaspora-restaurant-decoration; (d) the persistent
// media-conflation with Yazidis (a distinct Kurdish religion, NOT
// Zoroastrian, with their own Tawûsê Melek peacock-angel cosmology); the
// Bahá'í Faith (founded 1844 in Persia, a distinct religion with Shia-
// Islamic + Zoroastrian + Babi roots that is NOT a Zoroastrian
// denomination); (e) the "fire-worshipper" misreading (Zoroastrians do
// not worship fire — they pray toward the fire as the visible-symbol of
// Asha-as-light, distinct from worship-of-the-fire itself, a distinction
// the Greek Herodotus 1.131 already noted in the 5th c. BCE but Western
// polemic has flattened ever since); (f) the canonical-Magi of the
// Gospel of Matthew 2:1-12 as the only direct New-Testament-borrowing
// of a Zoroastrian institution (the magi being the Median-and-Persian
// priestly-caste of Zarathustra's tradition — the three wise men from
// the East were canonically Zoroastrian priest-astrologers); (g) the
// contemporary Parsi-community demographic crisis (under 60,000 Parsis
// worldwide as of 2020, the strict-endogamy rules preventing growth,
// the Bombay Doongerwadi towers-of-silence ritual under sustained legal
// and ecological pressure); (h) Freddie Mercury (Farrokh Bulsara,
// 1946-1991, Parsi Zoroastrian from Zanzibar) whose 1991 Kensal Green
// funeral was conducted by Zoroastrian priests in Avestan — almost no
// Western media coverage knew or noted the religious context.

